Media notes: Clark's Nutcracker, present since Nov 3rd, 2007 in the southwest corner of the southern Pines are of Illinois Beach State Park.  3rd Illinois record, 2nd in last century, 1st one ever photographed.   Bird seen here was either 'stealing' cached seeds stored by other birds or digging for insects, under the dead Austrian Pine tree bark.  Most often the bird fed on Pine cone seeds at the tops of the shorter Austrian Pine trees.
Observation Details: Continuing bird I had originally found on Nov 3rd (and ultimately only stayed 1 more day).  Despite today's strong winds, this bird actively fed, seemingly digging for cached nuts (by other birds) or insects and regularly seen near tops of short Austrian Pines, feeding on Pine cone seeds.  See Nov 3rd account at https://ebird.org/view/checklist/S50671013, for additional photos and original sighting details of this vagrant.    This is the 3rd Illinois record, 2nd in last century and 1st one photographed in the state. Observation Details: Minimum exact count. At least 8-10 birds visible throughout the count period, within a 20 m radius. Seen actively feeding on Ponderosa Pine cones on the ground and on horizontal Aspen and Ponderosa limbs. Noted birds flying to perches carrying cones in their bills; using their bills to turn a cone apparently to a side not yet probed; and typically making loud wing flaps when taking off. At one point I heard one nutcracker make a rapid series of at least 4 rough "krah" calls, and all the birds on the ground immediately flew up. Within less than 30 seconds several had flown back down - I suspected that the call functioned as an alarm, but was apparently a false alarm. Later, I observed 1 nutcracker fly in to where another had been working on a cone for several minutes and displace the sedentary bird. The displaced bird perched on an Aspen limb 1-2 m higher and made a loud downslurred "peeur" call several times. The displacer poked halfheartedly at the cone, then moved on, leaving it propped in a fork of the horizontal Aspen branch. I did not observe any caching behavior, though there was definitely some movement of birds to and from the aspen grove. I got some excellent videos of birds feeding on cones. Review of some of the footage shows the birds using their feet to manipulate and hold a cone while stabbing at it with their bill, using an outward prying motion to open cone scales. In some of the footage, birds are seen consuming several seeds, one at a time. Were they perhaps filling their sublingual pouch, then departing to cache seeds elsewhere?

Observation Details: Minimum exact count. At least 8-10 birds visible throughout the count period, within a 20 m radius. Seen actively feeding on Ponderosa Pine cones on the ground and on horizontal Aspen and Ponderosa limbs. Noted birds flying to perches carrying cones in their bills; using their bills to turn a cone apparently to a side not yet probed; and typically making loud wing flaps when taking off. At one point I heard one nutcracker make a rapid series of at least 4 rough "krah" calls, and all the birds on the ground immediately flew up. Within less than 30 seconds several had flown back down - I suspected that the call functioned as an alarm, but was apparently a false alarm. Later, I observed 1 nutcracker fly in to where another had been working on a cone for several minutes and displace the sedentary bird. The displaced bird perched on an Aspen limb 1-2 m higher and made a loud downslurred "peeur" call several times. The displacer poked halfheartedly at the cone, then moved on, leaving it propped in a fork of the horizontal Aspen branch. I did not observe any caching behavior, though there was definitely some movement of birds to and from the aspen grove. I got some excellent videos of birds feeding on cones. Review of some of the footage shows the birds using their feet to manipulate and hold a cone while stabbing at it with their bill, using an outward prying motion to open cone scales. In some of the footage, birds are seen consuming several seeds, one at a time. Were they perhaps filling their sublingual pouch, then departing to cache seeds elsewhere?

I hiked up to the top of the ridge east of the road and could hear the birds calling farther east up the valley. A fifth bird continued to call from the burn, then flew down near me to drink from the creek (ML76475761).  It then flew in the same direction as the previous four and out of sight to the east (ML76475721, ML76475731).

Observation Details: Spotted the first one at a distance as it was perched at the very top of a pine tree, digging into pine cones and eating the seeds. It flew to a closer tree, and as I was taking pictures, it flew off again to another pine across the parking lot. As I was trying to relocate it, it began vocalizing, and suddenly, a second bird joined in. I followed the sounds and saw two Clark's Nutcrackers in the same tree, one branch apart, communicating with each other. As I tried to position myself to get both birds in one frame, one of them flew off. These birds are about the size of a Scrub Jay, but heftier. Gray overall with black wings that appear navy blue; white undertail coverts; and a dark, decurved bill.

Observation Details: Found yesterday by Frank Verga on Greenwood Way. Refound by Carole Rose this morning; photos and notes. DR writes: "Although Carole initially refound these 3 nutcrackers on Greenwood Wary, they flew northwest along the ridge, where they were rediscovered on Wyndemere Way, flying back towards Greenwood Way. Those of us waiting at that spot encountered them singly as they flew in, but all 3 ended up high in a Monterey Pine at Greenwood Way and Greenwood Rise. Here the 3 nutcrackers were quiet and elusive, seemingly disappearing into the pine fronds, and eventually we saw they were pulling pine nuts out of pine-cones. One would occasionally fly to another tree for a time, but ended up at the favored pine again. In the hour or so we spent with them, I think they only called 3 times -- a loud, raspy "kraa-a-a," sometimes uttered twice -- but 99% of the time they were quiet and very easily overlooked."
With pictures

Observation Details: Absolutely amazing! Three birds flew up from beneath the trail about 0.3 miles from Mt Wrightson peak. Grayish bodies, black wings, white in tail and wing. Two birds flew into the group of pine trees above the trail where I lost them, while one landed right in front of me! Fantastic opportunity to photograph this amazing species while it fed on pine seeds from ripe pine cones. It stayed for about a minute before heading into the pines where the other two birds were hidden.  Perhaps these are the birds that were seen earlier in the year in this area?

Observation Details: Recorded begging

One banded adult feeding a juvenile.   Info from BBL: ‘I have been notified by the Bird Banding Lab (see below), that you saw one of my color banded Clark's nutcrackers at Crater Lake!  That is very exciting, and I appreciate you for reporting this bird.  In 2016, as a PhD student, I was awarded a research grant by the Science and Learning Center at Crater Lake National Park.  My research project studied the foraging behavior and spatial cognition in nutcrackers that frequented the areas along Rim Drive, where much human-food supplementation occurs.  I then compared the foraging behavior to what I observed in nutcrackers that lived in several areas within the park far from Rim Drive.  To conduct this study, I caught nutcrackers in walk-in traps and applied unique combinations of color bands to their legs so I could identify them again in the wild.  I found that nutcrackers that lived far from the human-food supplemented areas along Rim Drive cached more food in comparison to those nutcrackers that were seen at Rim Drive.  Due to the very small sample size and time scale during which this project was conducted, I have not yet been able to publish these results.  I am happy to see one of our subjects is still alive 3 years later.  I am also happy to answer any additional questions you might have about me, CLNU, or my research.  Best, Kelsey McCune’

Observation Details: Minimum exact count. At least 8-10 birds visible throughout the count period, within a 20 m radius. Seen actively feeding on Ponderosa Pine cones on the ground and on horizontal Aspen and Ponderosa limbs. Noted birds flying to perches carrying cones in their bills; using their bills to turn a cone apparently to a side not yet probed; and typically making loud wing flaps when taking off. At one point I heard one nutcracker make a rapid series of at least 4 rough "krah" calls, and all the birds on the ground immediately flew up. Within less than 30 seconds several had flown back down - I suspected that the call functioned as an alarm, but was apparently a false alarm. Later, I observed 1 nutcracker fly in to where another had been working on a cone for several minutes and displace the sedentary bird. The displaced bird perched on an Aspen limb 1-2 m higher and made a loud downslurred "peeur" call several times. The displacer poked halfheartedly at the cone, then moved on, leaving it propped in a fork of the horizontal Aspen branch. I did not observe any caching behavior, though there was definitely some movement of birds to and from the aspen grove. I got some excellent videos of birds feeding on cones. Review of some of the footage shows the birds using their feet to manipulate and hold a cone while stabbing at it with their bill, using an outward prying motion to open cone scales. In some of the footage, birds are seen consuming several seeds, one at a time. Were they perhaps filling their sublingual pouch, then departing to cache seeds elsewhere?

There might have been a third that flew over then the two first showed up - did not see it well. The two foraged for quite a while in the Ponderosas S and E of the cistern. For several minutes, there were 3 BBMA in the tree with them and I observed some agonistic behavior (see recording for details). The BBMA were silent while in the tree; the CLNU made some calls that were notably different from the calls I hear more often from them.  After the BBMA left, the nutcrackers were basically nonvocal while foraging. Observation Details: Some of these birds were banded.  I emailed and received the following response from a PhD student at the University of Washington:  "Those color-banded Clark's Nutcrackers you saw are part of a research project that I am currently conducting.  Those two birds were caught and banded in June, and we use those color bands to tell individuals apart.  I'm a PhD student at the University of Washington studying environmental influences on learning in birds.  Crater Lake National Park funded me to color band some Nutcrackers around the rim and in lower human-use areas to compare behavior and learning ability.  It's possible that the mass amount of exposure to humans (and feeding) that the birds around the rim experience has changed their natural behavior and ability to learn. "

Rare: "Unreported"--Continuing rarity in rocky grassland near the summit. First seen on first ascent in early morning flying downslope to the southwest. Later, maybe the same individual hopped slowly but deliberately up towards the trail through the rocky grass, eventually coming within 20 ft of us and other birders. We later got within ten feet of it for great looks off the south slope of the summit. 'The bird knows what he's doing' '"I know I'm pretty, take my photo!'" The bird then cheerily hopped and flew farther downslope until it was out of sight. We didn't see it for the last 90 minutes of our log. Remarkable that this species is here, far removed from it's normal dry conifer/rocky habitat. Nolan has photos. Caleb has digibin photos, his first ever of any bird.

Clark's Nutcracker, 1st photographed bird for Illinois.  Typical flight behavior of pulling its wings fully into body during its undulating flight.  Found in southwest corner of IBSP South Unit's South Pines.
Observation Details: Found around 8:45 am in southwest corner of Pine lot, when I had rested and then looked up hoping to see something wonderfully in the creation and lo and behold, a bird began making an awful crow-like, loud, guttural song and then flew in (see photos). It was a Clark's Nutcracker! This bird was present until Nov 7th and a few other birders saw it during those intervening dates.  All legit sightings were of this bird in the southwest corner of Pines (i.e. report of the bird at the Dead River was a misidentification, as someone was watching it in the south Pines section at that time).  See eBird Nov 6th report for better photos of bird.  Only the 6th Illinois report (but 3 have no documentation and are likely incorrect).  This is only the 3rd record for Illinois, only the 2nd one in the last century (the 9 Oct 1894 Evanston Lighthouse record being the 1st record).  This is the 1st one photographed in Illinois.  Out west in the Rockies, there were a number of reports of Clark's Nutcracker's being seen outside of the mountains and there usual range, so it was a form of an irruption year for them, thus helping increase the chances of this one showing up here along Lake Michigan.  The original IBET post from that morning was, "I was out birding this morning in a pine lot in northeast Lake County and hadn't come up with anything unusual all morning, so I literally stretched my hands out and asked the Creator God to "reveal His creation to me", which meant to me to come across something alittle different and unexpected. Within a minute of that, I began to hear a bird that sounded almost like a Raven's gutteral call. Knowing that species had recently been seen in this area, I was hoping it would be that bird.  I certainly did find a vagrant of the Corvid family, but it turned out to be a CLARK'S NUTCRACKER! It continued to call for a couple minutes before flying over to another Pine after which it soon left. It only was present for about 5 minutes. I was able to secure a number of perched and flight shots of this Nutcracker and I'll post some later today or tomorrow.  I wanted to get this info out there immediately for those who might want to explore for this species. The last direction the bird was heading would take it to Lyons Woods Forest Preserve, which has sufficient habitat to hold it for a few hours. For those who can't make it up here, it's worth mentioned that Wilmette's Gillson Park has some great habitat where it might pass through. Also, Evanston's Northwestern Landfill has pines, although not as old or as tall as Gillson's. There's already a very old record of this species in that area, so keep an eye out this afternoon and tomorrow morning at those locations.  To help find the bird, listen for a strange call that sounds Raven-like. Also, it exclusively stayed in the tops of the pines while calling.  This is only the 3rd record in Illinois history for this species. The first state record was collected on Oct 9th, 1894 from a location that is now the Evanston Arts Center (between Gillson and Northwestern). There were numerous records in the upper Midwest in the year before and after this sighting, so they must have been moving through the Midwest back then. The 2nd state record was a bird that I believe was in west-central Illinois a few winters ago, coming to a feeder. I think it died and the specimen was collected before the birding community was made aware of it.  This sighing gives a reasonable, albiet fairly low, chance at seein it in IL. I plan on going out to Lyons Woods right now and if I relocate it, I'll post again before 1 pm.  Eric Walters Zion, IL November 03, 2007, 10:40 AM"  Also, see Nov 6th account at https://ebird.org/view/checklist/S50683994, for additional photos of this bird feeding on Pine cone seeds and looking for cached seeds/insects in Austrian Pines.

Found by UW-Madison Audubon Society chapter group who pointed it out to me as I approached them around 9:30am on the hike/bike trail across Moorland Road from E-Way parking lot. When I finally realized what the group was pointing at, I was right next to the bird, only 5-10 feet away as it foraged on the grass edging the paved trail. After perching on a speed limit sign and a no parking sign, foraging again on the trailside grass, and perching on an overhead electric wire, it eventually moved to the E-Way parking lot side of road. Photos show: grey overall, heavy jet black bill; solid black wings on the standing bird; tail square with pattern from above (visible in flight) broad white laterally (several rectrices) and black centrally, when perched tail white from below. Body larger and much more bulky, wings more black, and bill much heavier than Northern Mockingbird. Spent considerable time foraging on mowed grassy areas. Seen by around 20 or more others in addition to the UW group by the time I left the site at about 10:25am. Very tolerant of people nearby including walking right below it on the hike/bike trail when it was perched on the roadside wires.

One banded adult feeding a juvenile.   Info from BBL: ‘I have been notified by the Bird Banding Lab (see below), that you saw one of my color banded Clark's nutcrackers at Crater Lake!  That is very exciting, and I appreciate you for reporting this bird.  In 2016, as a PhD student, I was awarded a research grant by the Science and Learning Center at Crater Lake National Park.  My research project studied the foraging behavior and spatial cognition in nutcrackers that frequented the areas along Rim Drive, where much human-food supplementation occurs.  I then compared the foraging behavior to what I observed in nutcrackers that lived in several areas within the park far from Rim Drive.  To conduct this study, I caught nutcrackers in walk-in traps and applied unique combinations of color bands to their legs so I could identify them again in the wild.  I found that nutcrackers that lived far from the human-food supplemented areas along Rim Drive cached more food in comparison to those nutcrackers that were seen at Rim Drive.  Due to the very small sample size and time scale during which this project was conducted, I have not yet been able to publish these results.  I am happy to see one of our subjects is still alive 3 years later.  I am also happy to answer any additional questions you might have about me, CLNU, or my research.  Best, Kelsey McCune’

Minimum exact count. At least 8-10 birds visible throughout the count period, within a 20 m radius. Seen actively feeding on Ponderosa Pine cones on the ground and on horizontal Aspen and Ponderosa limbs. Noted birds flying to perches carrying cones in their bills; using their bills to turn a cone apparently to a side not yet probed; and typically making loud wing flaps when taking off. At one point I heard one nutcracker make a rapid series of at least 4 rough "krah" calls, and all the birds on the ground immediately flew up. Within less than 30 seconds several had flown back down - I suspected that the call functioned as an alarm, but was apparently a false alarm. Later, I observed 1 nutcracker fly in to where another had been working on a cone for several minutes and displace the sedentary bird. The displaced bird perched on an Aspen limb 1-2 m higher and made a loud downslurred "peeur" call several times. The displacer poked halfheartedly at the cone, then moved on, leaving it propped in a fork of the horizontal Aspen branch. I did not observe any caching behavior, though there was definitely some movement of birds to and from the aspen grove. I got some excellent videos of birds feeding on cones. Review of some of the footage shows the birds using their feet to manipulate and hold a cone while stabbing at it with their bill, using an outward prying motion to open cone scales. In some of the footage, birds are seen consuming several seeds, one at a time. Were they perhaps filling their sublingual pouch, then departing to cache seeds elsewhere?

After some searching, we eventually saw two birds perched together in oaks and pines along the ridge to the southeast of the meadow, and later one bird foraging in the tree where these birds were initially located earlier in the morning along the trail a short distance to the southwest.  When foraging in the dead pine, the one bird picked at the needle clusters at the tips of the branches.  These birds occasionally gave scratchy, "caaarr" calls in addition to a harsh rattle that was not unlike a call by a Steller's Jay.  These birds flew widely about the area, but they also readily perched in the open, often at the very top of a tree.  These were large jays, yet they appeared more like small crows given their more stocky structure.  The bill was almost as long as head was wide, in that it would have extended back beyond the auriculars if reversed on the head.  The culmen was slightly decurved and the bill tapered to a sharply pointed tip.  The forehead was gently sloping and the crown was weakly rounded on a head that appeared quite large in proportion to the body.  The neck was short and inconspicuous, and the body was plump with a posture that approached diagonal when the birds perched atop the trees.  The wings were conspicuously long, with wingtips that reached almost all that way to the tip of the tail, but I failed to note the primary projection precisely, even though I am confident that it was also quite long.  The medium-length tail was about as long as the body without the head, it was parallel-sided, and squared-off at the tip.  The long undertail-coverts further accentuated the short appearance of the tail.  The legs were stout, but of unremarkable length.  These were boldly marked birds given the contrast between the mostly black wings and the light to medium-gray shades of the head, back, and underparts.  The immediate forehead, chin, and the area around the eyes was white, and on one of the birds, a narrow band of white encircled the gray auriculars.  The back and scapulars were unmarked, but the wings were almost entirely black.  I noted that the secondaries were mostly white in the closed wing, but the innermost feathers appeared to be black.  The primaries were entirely black, but the primary coverts on the bird I saw best were brown, as apparently was a feather or two associated with the alula.  The undertail coverts were snow-white, so they contrasted sharply with the gray belly along a line that extended straight across the vent.  The spread wings were rounded and conspicuously broad when seen in flight, and they seemed to be mostly black apart from a large, white speculum in the secondaries.  The bill was black, the eyes were conspicuously dark, and when seen in good light, apparently dark brown.  The legs and feet were dull blackish.

Minimum exact count. At least 8-10 birds visible throughout the count period, within a 20 m radius. Seen actively feeding on Ponderosa Pine cones on the ground and on horizontal Aspen and Ponderosa limbs. Noted birds flying to perches carrying cones in their bills; using their bills to turn a cone apparently to a side not yet probed; and typically making loud wing flaps when taking off. At one point I heard one nutcracker make a rapid series of at least 4 rough "krah" calls, and all the birds on the ground immediately flew up. Within less than 30 seconds several had flown back down - I suspected that the call functioned as an alarm, but was apparently a false alarm. Later, I observed 1 nutcracker fly in to where another had been working on a cone for several minutes and displace the sedentary bird. The displaced bird perched on an Aspen limb 1-2 m higher and made a loud downslurred "peeur" call several times. The displacer poked halfheartedly at the cone, then moved on, leaving it propped in a fork of the horizontal Aspen branch. I did not observe any caching behavior, though there was definitely some movement of birds to and from the aspen grove. I got some excellent videos of birds feeding on cones. Review of some of the footage shows the birds using their feet to manipulate and hold a cone while stabbing at it with their bill, using an outward prying motion to open cone scales. In some of the footage, birds are seen consuming several seeds, one at a time. Were they perhaps filling their sublingual pouch, then departing to cache seeds elsewhere?

Some of these birds were banded.  I emailed and received the following response from a PhD student at the University of Washington:  "Those color-banded Clark's Nutcrackers you saw are part of a research project that I am currently conducting.  Those two birds were caught and banded in June, and we use those color bands to tell individuals apart.  I'm a PhD student at the University of Washington studying environmental influences on learning in birds.  Crater Lake National Park funded me to color band some Nutcrackers around the rim and in lower human-use areas to compare behavior and learning ability.  It's possible that the mass amount of exposure to humans (and feeding) that the birds around the rim experience has changed their natural behavior and ability to learn. "

Observation Details: Large jay-like bird. Gray body, black wing, black bill. In flight, white secondary feathers and outer tail feathers. Continuing flock. Relocated at 1000, about 100 yards north of NC post location and about 200 yards north of TH sighting yesterday (so seem to be staying in general area). Spent 3.5 hrs in the area before we located them on west side of road fork that runs up canyon (northwest, or right, when entering area on road from east) from the reported 'Y' in the road. First seen on ground, then watched them forage about from ground to lower story to ground again, covering maybe 100 yards moving a little further up canyon. Birds were almost totally mute. Only a few quiet call notes expressed over a 30 min watch. Very first rough count was 'at least 7,' but lastly, all bunched up close, went into the lower/mid story of some trees almost at once, giving us a rough count of 14. Then they filtered out from these trees by twos and threes and seemed to just go on and on. Photos to add later.

Continuing. Light grey bird with black wings, white outer tail feathers and white secondary wing feathers obvious when flying. First, around 9:10am, we saw one bird fly into huge pine tree about at Nancy C’s first pin (32.88066° N, 116.45433° W), on Big Laguna Trail at intersection with Laguna Campground Trail. It vocalized only once. It worked pine cones for only a minute or so then flew back southwest across the meadow into pines. Checking pines across the meadow and (32.87981° N, 116.45570° W) produced two additional birds, one making several rattling calls. Later, around 1:45pm, we saw two Clark’s Nutcrackers in group of pines isolated on a small hill at 32.87865° N, 116.45954° W, just east of the southern end of Big Laguna Lake. One of those birds eventually flew west across the lake into the pine forest.

Continuing.  I parked in the pullout at MP 19 and walked about 1/3 mile to the trailhead on the W side of the road.  I took trail 7 almost to the large meadow - perhaps 1/2 mile.  Right before the meadow area, there is a bit of a hill on the right Eg and another higher to the left NW.  I heard the raspy call from the small hill on the right and found 3 nutcrackers close together.  After watching them for a while, I decided to check out the larger hill to the NW.  Within 45 minutes, the 3 nutcrackers were on that hill - both in pines and working bark in dead trees.  One way to locate is to listen for large pieces of bark falling.  They stayed in this area most of the time and did not seem to mind an observer close by.  In addition to the nasally/screech call they sometimes did a high pitched "mew" like a cat.

first saw one nutcracker fly out of trees near the overlook heading to the southwest. Fairly soon after I spotted another nutcracker fly into another tree and wasn't positive it was a second individual versus the first one circling back. I then heard a nutcracker calling in the distance in the direction I saw the first individual fly toward. The second bird then flew away and I still heard one bird calling. Later spotted a nutcracker in trees over the lake and heard a second one calling, then I heard two different types of calling back and forth and finally saw 2 nutcrackers fly off coming from different trees. I had hiked up to an existing trail that overlooked the lake when I finally spotted the two individuals flying away to the southwest. Photo to follow this report.

Apparently foraging at the edge of the big meadow south-southwest of the main parking lot. Perching at heights of 15-30 feet on dead branches of noble fir and sallying out repeatedly. Large mostly plain pale gray passerine with black wings and tail and white wing patch. Dagger-like blackish bill. Broad wings and relatively short tail. Time approximately 12:30. Habitat seems fairly typical (high elevation conifer forest broken by meadows), but apparently rare in the Coast Range at this time of year as this seems to be the first June ebird record for the county.

Media notes: One of three traveling together
Observation Details: Found yesterday by Frank Verga on Greenwood Way. Refound by Carole Rose this morning; photos and notes. DR writes: "Although Carole initially refound these 3 nutcrackers on Greenwood Wary, they flew northwest along the ridge, where they were rediscovered on Wyndemere Way, flying back towards Greenwood Way. Those of us waiting at that spot encountered them singly as they flew in, but all 3 ended up high in a Monterey Pine at Greenwood Way and Greenwood Rise. Here the 3 nutcrackers were quiet and elusive, seemingly disappearing into the pine fronds, and eventually we saw they were pulling pine nuts out of pine-cones. One would occasionally fly to another tree for a time, but ended up at the favored pine again. In the hour or so we spent with them, I think they only called 3 times -- a loud, raspy "kraa-a-a," sometimes uttered twice -- but 99% of the time they were quiet and very easily overlooked."

A great find yesterday by Frank Verga in his neighborhood on Greenwood Way. Refound this morning by Carole Rose. These birds like to be way up top and only occasionally vocalized. At least for today, they seemed to have a circuit that took them up and around the tall pines on Greenwood Way and back to the vicinity of Greenwood Rise/Vale intersection.

Minimum exact count. At least 8-10 birds visible throughout the count period, within a 20 m radius. Seen actively feeding on Ponderosa Pine cones on the ground and on horizontal Aspen and Ponderosa limbs. Noted birds flying to perches carrying cones in their bills; using their bills to turn a cone apparently to a side not yet probed; and typically making loud wing flaps when taking off. At one point I heard one nutcracker make a rapid series of at least 4 rough "krah" calls, and all the birds on the ground immediately flew up. Within less than 30 seconds several had flown back down - I suspected that the call functioned as an alarm, but was apparently a false alarm. Later, I observed 1 nutcracker fly in to where another had been working on a cone for several minutes and displace the sedentary bird. The displaced bird perched on an Aspen limb 1-2 m higher and made a loud downslurred "peeur" call several times. The displacer poked halfheartedly at the cone, then moved on, leaving it propped in a fork of the horizontal Aspen branch. I did not observe any caching behavior, though there was definitely some movement of birds to and from the aspen grove. I got some excellent videos of birds feeding on cones. Review of some of the footage shows the birds using their feet to manipulate and hold a cone while stabbing at it with their bill, using an outward prying motion to open cone scales. In some of the footage, birds are seen consuming several seeds, one at a time. Were they perhaps filling their sublingual pouch, then departing to cache seeds elsewhere?

I emailed and received the following response from a PhD student at the University of Washington:  "Those color-banded Clark's Nutcrackers you saw are part of a research project that I am currently conducting.  Those two birds were caught and banded in June, and we use those color bands to tell individuals apart.  I'm a PhD student at the University of Washington studying environmental influences on learning in birds.  Crater Lake National Park funded me to color band some Nutcrackers around the rim and in lower human-use areas to compare behavior and learning ability.  It's possible that the mass amount of exposure to humans (and feeding) that the birds around the rim experience has changed their natural behavior and ability to learn. "

Large jay-like bird. Gray body, black wing, black bill. In flight, white secondary feathers and outer tail feathers. Continuing flock. Relocated at 1000, about 100 yards north of NC post location and about 200 yards north of TH sighting yesterday (so seem to be staying in general area). Spent 3.5 hrs in the area before we located them on west side of road fork that runs up canyon (northwest, or right, when entering area on road from east) from the reported 'Y' in the road. First seen on ground, then watched them forage about from ground to lower story to ground again, covering maybe 100 yards moving a little further up canyon. Birds were almost totally mute. Only a few quiet call notes expressed over a 30 min watch. Very first rough count was 'at least 7,' but lastly, all bunched up close, went into the lower/mid story of some trees almost at once, giving us a rough count of 14. Then they filtered out from these trees by twos and threes and seemed to just go on and on. Photos to add later.

Media notes: Clark's Nutcracker, present since Nov 3rd, 2007 in the southwest corner of the southern Pines are of Illinois Beach State Park.  3rd Illinois record, 2nd in last century, 1st one ever photographed.   Most often the bird fed on Pine cone seeds at the tops of the shorter Austrian Pine trees, as seen here.  A few other times it was seen 'stealing' cached seeds stored by other birds or digging for insects, under the dead Austrian Pine tree bark.
Observation Details: Continuing bird I had originally found on Nov 3rd (and ultimately only stayed 1 more day).  Despite today's strong winds, this bird actively fed, seemingly digging for cached nuts (by other birds) or insects and regularly seen near tops of short Austrian Pines, feeding on Pine cone seeds.  See Nov 3rd account at https://ebird.org/view/checklist/S50671013, for additional photos and original sighting details of this vagrant.    This is the 3rd Illinois record, 2nd in last century and 1st one photographed in the state.  A few other birders saw this bird during its time in the southwest corner of the southern Pines area (i.e. nobody saw the bird outside of this fairly small section of the Pines).

Locality: Rancho Del Oso Pardo, Colorado--Ridge Trail (private)

Observation Details: After some searching, we eventually saw two birds perched together in oaks and pines along the ridge to the southeast of the meadow, and later one bird foraging in the tree where these birds were initially located earlier in the morning along the trail a short distance to the southwest.  When foraging in the dead pine, the one bird picked at the needle clusters at the tips of the branches.  These birds occasionally gave scratchy, "caaarr" calls in addition to a harsh rattle that was not unlike a call by a Steller's Jay.  These birds flew widely about the area, but they also readily perched in the open, often at the very top of a tree.  These were large jays, yet they appeared more like small crows given their more stocky structure.  The bill was almost as long as head was wide, in that it would have extended back beyond the auriculars if reversed on the head.  The culmen was slightly decurved and the bill tapered to a sharply pointed tip.  The forehead was gently sloping and the crown was weakly rounded on a head that appeared quite large in proportion to the body.  The neck was short and inconspicuous, and the body was plump with a posture that approached diagonal when the birds perched atop the trees.  The wings were conspicuously long, with wingtips that reached almost all that way to the tip of the tail, but I failed to note the primary projection precisely, even though I am confident that it was also quite long.  The medium-length tail was about as long as the body without the head, it was parallel-sided, and squared-off at the tip.  The long undertail-coverts further accentuated the short appearance of the tail.  The legs were stout, but of unremarkable length.  These were boldly marked birds given the contrast between the mostly black wings and the light to medium-gray shades of the head, back, and underparts.  The immediate forehead, chin, and the area around the eyes was white, and on one of the birds, a narrow band of white encircled the gray auriculars.  The back and scapulars were unmarked, but the wings were almost entirely black.  I noted that the secondaries were mostly white in the closed wing, but the innermost feathers appeared to be black.  The primaries were entirely black, but the primary coverts on the bird I saw best were brown, as apparently was a feather or two associated with the alula.  The undertail coverts were snow-white, so they contrasted sharply with the gray belly along a line that extended straight across the vent.  The spread wings were rounded and conspicuously broad when seen in flight, and they seemed to be mostly black apart from a large, white speculum in the secondaries.  The bill was black, the eyes were conspicuously dark, and when seen in good light, apparently dark brown.  The legs and feet were dull blackish.

Media notes: Clark's Nutcracker, 1st photographed bird for Illinois.  Found in southwest corner of IBSP South Unit's South Pines.
Observation Details: Found around 8:45 am in southwest corner of Pine lot, when I had rested and then looked up hoping to see something wonderfully in the creation and lo and behold, a bird began making an awful crow-like, loud, guttural song and then flew in (see photos). It was a Clark's Nutcracker! This bird was present until Nov 7th and a few other birders saw it during those intervening dates.  All legit sightings were of this bird in the southwest corner of Pines (i.e. report of the bird at the Dead River was a misidentification, as someone was watching it in the south Pines section at that time).  See eBird Nov 6th report for better photos of bird.  Only the 6th Illinois report (but 3 have no documentation and are likely incorrect).  This is only the 3rd record for Illinois, only the 2nd one in the last century (the 9 Oct 1894 Evanston Lighthouse record being the 1st record).  This is the 1st one photographed in Illinois.  Out west in the Rockies, there were a number of reports of Clark's Nutcracker's being seen outside of the mountains and there usual range, so it was a form of an irruption year for them, thus helping increase the chances of this one showing up here along Lake Michigan.  The original IBET post from that morning was, "I was out birding this morning in a pine lot in northeast Lake County and hadn't come up with anything unusual all morning, so I literally stretched my hands out and asked the Creator God to "reveal His creation to me", which meant to me to come across something alittle different and unexpected. Within a minute of that, I began to hear a bird that sounded almost like a Raven's gutteral call. Knowing that species had recently been seen in this area, I was hoping it would be that bird.  I certainly did find a vagrant of the Corvid family, but it turned out to be a CLARK'S NUTCRACKER! It continued to call for a couple minutes before flying over to another Pine after which it soon left. It only was present for about 5 minutes. I was able to secure a number of perched and flight shots of this Nutcracker and I'll post some later today or tomorrow.  I wanted to get this info out there immediately for those who might want to explore for this species. The last direction the bird was heading would take it to Lyons Woods Forest Preserve, which has sufficient habitat to hold it for a few hours. For those who can't make it up here, it's worth mentioned that Wilmette's Gillson Park has some great habitat where it might pass through. Also, Evanston's Northwestern Landfill has pines, although not as old or as tall as Gillson's. There's already a very old record of this species in that area, so keep an eye out this afternoon and tomorrow morning at those locations.  To help find the bird, listen for a strange call that sounds Raven-like. Also, it exclusively stayed in the tops of the pines while calling.  This is only the 3rd record in Illinois history for this species. The first state record was collected on Oct 9th, 1894 from a location that is now the Evanston Arts Center (between Gillson and Northwestern). There were numerous records in the upper Midwest in the year before and after this sighting, so they must have been moving through the Midwest back then. The 2nd state record was a bird that I believe was in west-central Illinois a few winters ago, coming to a feeder. I think it died and the specimen was collected before the birding community was made aware of it.  This sighing gives a reasonable, albiet fairly low, chance at seein it in IL. I plan on going out to Lyons Woods right now and if I relocate it, I'll post again before 1 pm.  Eric Walters Zion, IL November 03, 2007, 10:40 AM"  Also, see Nov 6th account at https://ebird.org/view/checklist/S50683994, for additional photos of this bird feeding on Pine cone seeds and looking for cached seeds/insects in Austrian Pines.

Found yesterday by Frank Verga on Greenwood Way. Refound by Carole Rose this morning; photos and notes. DR writes: "Although Carole initially refound these 3 nutcrackers on Greenwood Wary, they flew northwest along the ridge, where they were rediscovered on Wyndemere Way, flying back towards Greenwood Way. Those of us waiting at that spot encountered them singly as they flew in, but all 3 ended up high in a Monterey Pine at Greenwood Way and Greenwood Rise. Here the 3 nutcrackers were quiet and elusive, seemingly disappearing into the pine fronds, and eventually we saw they were pulling pine nuts out of pine-cones. One would occasionally fly to another tree for a time, but ended up at the favored pine again. In the hour or so we spent with them, I think they only called 3 times -- a loud, raspy "kraa-a-a," sometimes uttered twice -- but 99% of the time they were quiet and very easily overlooked."

Continuing. Light grey bird with black wings, white outer tail feathers and white secondary wing feathers obvious when flying. First, around 9:10am, we saw one bird fly into huge pine tree about at Nancy C’s first pin (32.88066° N, 116.45433° W), on Big Laguna Trail at intersection with Laguna Campground Trail. It vocalized only once. It worked pine cones for only a minute or so then flew back southwest across the meadow into pines. Checking pines across the meadow and (32.87981° N, 116.45570° W) produced two additional birds, one making several rattling calls. Later, around 1:45pm, we saw two Clark’s Nutcrackers in group of pines isolated on a small hill at 32.87865° N, 116.45954° W, just east of the southern end of Big Laguna Lake. One of those birds eventually flew west across the lake into the pine forest.

Light gray corvid with black wings, mostly-white tail, slim black bill. Feeding on pine cones in trio of loaded pine trees straddling trail intersection here: (32.8808157, -116.4541957) On several occasions, flew across the meadow to the east for several minutes, but always returned and spent most of the time in at the trail intersection. These pines must be especially good eating right now. Mostly silent, but one would call as others in the flock dispersed, a piercing loud “craaaaaa”. Found by Dave Trissel this morning. Our first of hopefully many county records this season, which seems to be an irruptive one for this species in California.

Found by UW-Madison Audubon Society chapter group who pointed it out to me as I approached them around 9:30am on the hike/bike trail across Moorland Road from E-Way parking lot. When I finally realized what the group was pointing at, I was right next to the bird, only 5-10 feet away as it foraged on the grass edging the paved trail. After perching on a speed limit sign and a no parking sign, foraging again on the trailside grass, and perching on an overhead electric wire, it eventually moved to the E-Way parking lot side of road. Photos show: grey overall, heavy jet black bill; solid black wings on the standing bird; tail square with pattern from above (visible in flight) broad white laterally (several rectrices) and black centrally, when perched tail white from below. Body larger and much more bulky, wings more black, and bill much heavier than Northern Mockingbird. Spent considerable time foraging on mowed grassy areas. Seen by around 20 or more others in addition to the UW group by the time I left the site at about 10:25am. Very tolerant of people nearby including walking right below it on the hike/bike trail when it was perched on the roadside wires.

Locality: Little Spokane River NA--Indian Painted Rocks

Observation Details: I first detected this bird when I heard its "kraaaaa" call.  I wasn't even thinking nutcracker here, so at first I thought it was a woodpecker.  As soon as I saw it, however, it was immediately identifiable as a Clark's Nutcracker.  Large crow-like bird with gray plumage; black wings and a mostly white tail.  It landed at the top of a cottonwood tree and perched there for several minutes before eventually flying to the ground.  It caught what appeared to be a whiptail scorpion that it carried back up into the tree to eat.  It was still in the woods when I left.

Locality: Bull Hill Guest Ranch  - central area (restricted access)

Observation Details: VERY abundant, actively caching pine seeds.  Estimated over several independent sections of trail and summed the estimates.  Probably a conservative estimate: may have been twice this many.  Copy of response to regional reviewer about this number: "I believe that 280 is a reasonably accurate estimate of the total number of birds seen.  There were several locations along the trail where I could simultaneously see 20+ individuals gathering seeds from pines.  Individual birds were coming and going, caching seeds in locations away from the pines, but the nutcrackers were not generally moving in groups.  The birds were concentrated in the stands of pines, but we were constantly passing many individual birds, often 3-4 in each tree, nearly continuously over the course of several miles.  I estimated 200 from the trailhead to Dollar Lakes, 50 from Dollar Lakes to Lamoille Lake, and 30 from Lamoille Lake back to the trailhead (loop trail, new ground covered).  Certainly, some individuals may have been seen twice, but based on the pattern of movement of individuals (not in groups), the rate of movement (most individuals staying in a tree until their crop was full), the total ground we covered, etc., I think 280 is a good estimate of the number of individuals.  I've spent a lot of time in CLNU habitat and I've never seen the species in density like this.  The number seems remarkable in the database and it was also remarkable to us in the field. "

Minimum exact count. At least 8-10 birds visible throughout the count period, within a 20 m radius. Seen actively feeding on Ponderosa Pine cones on the ground and on horizontal Aspen and Ponderosa limbs. Noted birds flying to perches carrying cones in their bills; using their bills to turn a cone apparently to a side not yet probed; and typically making loud wing flaps when taking off. At one point I heard one nutcracker make a rapid series of at least 4 rough "krah" calls, and all the birds on the ground immediately flew up. Within less than 30 seconds several had flown back down - I suspected that the call functioned as an alarm, but was apparently a false alarm. Later, I observed 1 nutcracker fly in to where another had been working on a cone for several minutes and displace the sedentary bird. The displaced bird perched on an Aspen limb 1-2 m higher and made a loud downslurred "peeur" call several times. The displacer poked halfheartedly at the cone, then moved on, leaving it propped in a fork of the horizontal Aspen branch. I did not observe any caching behavior, though there was definitely some movement of birds to and from the aspen grove. I got some excellent videos of birds feeding on cones. Review of some of the footage shows the birds using their feet to manipulate and hold a cone while stabbing at it with their bill, using an outward prying motion to open cone scales. In some of the footage, birds are seen consuming several seeds, one at a time. Were they perhaps filling their sublingual pouch, then departing to cache seeds elsewhere?

It flew out into the meadow to perch on one of the big logs where it would drop to the ground, catch something (grasshoppers?), and return to the log to eat it.  Eventually flew back to the trees to the north.

Continuing. Light grey bird with black wings, white outer tail feathers and white secondary wing feathers obvious when flying. First, around 9:10am, we saw one bird fly into huge pine tree about at Nancy C’s first pin (32.88066° N, 116.45433° W), on Big Laguna Trail at intersection with Laguna Campground Trail. It vocalized only once. It worked pine cones for only a minute or so then flew back southwest across the meadow into pines. Checking pines across the meadow and (32.87981° N, 116.45570° W) produced two additional birds, one making several rattling calls. Later, around 1:45pm, we saw two Clark’s Nutcrackers in group of pines isolated on a small hill at 32.87865° N, 116.45954° W, just east of the southern end of Big Laguna Lake. One of those birds eventually flew west across the lake into the pine forest.

Locality: Los Padres NF--Mt. Pinos Summit Trail (VEN)
Observation Details: These birds were everywhere! I’ve never seen so many! They were 3 large loose flocks feeding in the trees and on the ground as well as several individual flyovers. When feeding in the trees they were picking at the tree bark & popping off large chunks. They were also feeding on pine nuts from cones. Some were vocal, others quite. Usually we are lucky to see 2 or 3 at this location. The number of Clark’s nutcrackers observed on this trip was astounding.

Light gray corvid with black wings, mostly-white tail, slim black bill. Feeding on pine cones in trio of loaded pine trees straddling trail intersection here: (32.8808157, -116.4541957) On several occasions, flew across the meadow to the east for several minutes, but always returned and spent most of the time in at the trail intersection. These pines must be especially good eating right now. Mostly silent, but one would call as others in the flock dispersed, a piercing loud “craaaaaa”. Found by Dave Trissel this morning. Our first of hopefully many county records this season, which seems to be an irruptive one for this species in California.

Black wings and tail, with white tips of primaries which looked like a curved stripe around it's back as it perched. White outer tail feathers when it flew and white under tail coverts visible. Found by UW-Madison Audubon Society chapter group who pointed it out to me as I approached them around 9:30am on the hike/bike trail across Moorland Road from E-Way parking lot. When I finally realized what the group was pointing at, I was right next to the bird, only 5-10 feet away as it foraged on the grass edging the paved trail. After perching on a speed limit sign and a no parking sign, foraging again on the trailside grass, and perching on an overhead electric wire, it eventually moved to the E-Way parking lot side of road. Photos show: grey overall, heavy jet black bill; solid black wings on the standing bird; tail square with pattern from above (visible in flight) broad white laterally (several rectrices) and black centrally, when perched tail white from below. Body larger and much more bulky, wings more black, and bill much heavier than Northern Mockingbird. Spent considerable time foraging on mowed grassy areas. Seen by around 20 or more others in addition to the UW group by the time I left the site at about 10:25am. Very tolerant of people nearby including walking right below it on the hike/bike trail when it was perched on the roadside wires.

Continuing bird found by Ken Mullé on July 16.  A group of us assembled near the large live pine next to the two dead pines just past the gate in the afternoon. Before 3PM Jim Chiropolis spotted the Clark’s Nutcracker and I was able to get a clear view of it went into the top of the pine. It was significantly larger than our Scrub Jays. The graphic black wings with white patches, gray body with black and white tail really stood out. Getting clear views as it worked the cones near the top of the canopy was trickier. Once in the scope I had pretty good views of the long pointed bill as it hammered away. Digibins and digiscope photos. And I’m thinking of the excellent Russ Bright as he would have really gassed on this bird in his favorite county to bird.

Continuing bird.  Found on right side pine next to ridge fire-trail just before left to Seaview Trail.  Assisted by local David. Light gray corvid--jay sized with long thin slightly curved bill, dark wings, and prominent white tail.  Constantly worked the pinecones. ID photo.

Continuing. Found yesterday by Ken Mulle.  Gray corvid with black wings and  white secondaries. Juvenile based on Pyle 1997 as it appears because of brownish lesser coverts. It is considered a juvenile until September.
